context: For 2016, U.S. News & World Report ranked BYU as tied for <b5_0>66th<b5_0/> for national universities in the United States. A 2013 Quarterly Journal of Economics study of where the nation's top high school students choose to enroll ranked BYU <b6_0>No. 21<b6_0/> in its peer-reviewed study. <a2_0>The Princeton Review<a2_0/> has ranked BYU <b7_0>the best<b7_0/> value for college in 2007, and its library is consistently ranked in the nation's top ten — No. 1 in 2004 and No. 4 in 2007. BYU is also ranked No. 19 in the <a3_0>U.S. News and World Report's "Great Schools, Great Prices" lineup<a3_0/>, and No. 12 in lowest student-incurred debt. Due in part to the school's emphasis on undergraduate research, in rankings for 2008-2009, BYU was ranked <a4_0><b8_0>No. 10<b8_0/><a4_0/> nationally for the number of students who go on to earn PhDs, <b9_0>No. 1 nationally<b9_0/> for students who go on to dental school, No. 6 nationally for students who go on to law school, and No. 10 nationally for students who go on to medical school. BYU is designated as a research university with high research activity by the <a1_0>Carnegie Foundation for the Advancement of Teaching<a1_0/>.]] <a0_0>Forbes Magazine<a0_0/> ranked it as the No. 1 "Top University to Work For in 2014" and as the best college in Utah.
